<biogHist>
<abstract>A child known as an inmate was defined in the <span style="font-style:italic">Industrial and Reformatory Schools Act 1893</span> (s.5) as any child detained in an industrial or reformatory school. The <span style="font-style:italic">State Children Act 1907</span> (s.4) changed the definition to refer to a 'State child maintained in an institution'. The <span style="font-style:italic">State Children Act Amendment Act 1927</span> (s.3) substituted the term ward for State child. The institutions included Children's Homes, orphanages, industrial schools and reformatories. It is likely that the term was also used more generally to describe all children in institutions, not only those who were wards. The term was deleted from legislation by the <span style="font-style:italic">Child Welfare Act Amendment Act No.2 1976</span> (s.5k).</abstract>
<p>Inmate was a term used in the nineteeth and twentieth century in Western Australia to describe a child in institutions such as Children's Homes, orphanages, industrial schools and reformatories. In its legal sense, inmate had a specific meaning. The <span style="font-style:italic">Industrial and Reformatory Schools Act 1893</span> (s.5) included the definition of children and inmates in the same clause. An inmate was any child detained in an industrial or reformatory school under the provisions of the Act.</p>
<p>The <span style="font-style:italic">State Children Act 1907</span> (s.4) changed the definition to refer to a 'State child maintained in an institution'. The <span style="font-style:italic">State Children Act Amendment Act 1927</span> (s.3) substituted the term ward for State child and the definition of inmate in the <span style="font-style:italic">Child Welfare Act 1947</span> (s.4) continued this terminology: 'a ward maintained in an institution'. In practice, it is likely that the term, inmate was used generally by institutional authorities to describe all children in an institution, not only those who were State children or wards. However, as these definitions show, the term inmate did have a particular legal meaning.</p>
<p>The term was deleted from legislation by the <span style="font-style:italic">Child Welfare Act Amendment Act No.2 1976</span> (s.5k).</p>

</biogHist>
